The best approach for `File.*` and `Directory.*` is the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and provides a ready-made `IFileSystem` interface.

### 1. Install packages

```bash
dotnet add <YourProject> package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes

```csharp
public class ConfigManager(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool DirectoryExists(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});
// Pre-create the directory so Directory.Exists returns true
mockFs.AddDirectory("/data");

var manager = new ConfigManager(mockFs);

Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", manager.Load("/config.json"));
Assert.True(manager.DirectoryExists("/data"));
```

**Key points:**
- `IFileSystem` covers `File`, `Directory`, `Path`, and more under one interface
- `MockFileSystem` provides an in-memory filesystem — no temp files needed
- Register as **singleton** since `FileSystem` is stateless
- Don't build a custom wrapper — `System.IO.Abstractions` already handles every edge case

After installing the package and updating your classes, use the `migrate-static-to-wrapper` skill if you want help bulk-replacing all the `File.*`/`Directory.*` call sites across your project.
